---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Comments, Observations
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

The results measured and graphed are the total number of constraint checks
 evaluated BETWEEN parts of the program plan template.  This number DOES
 NOT include node consistency constraints, thus the result can be interpreted
 as if an indexing system gave a list of all statements of a particular type 
 at no cost. 

At noise levels of 500 statements, Test #1 has a 95% confidence 
 interval ranging between 109054 and 187728 checks.  Changing the first phase
 to a more efficient search strategy results in Test #2's 95% confidence 
 interval of between 20075 and 69562 checks.  Depending on the actual 
 search approach in DECODE, this suggests a substantial possible improvement 
 immediately through mapping to a CSP framework.  This improvement translates
 to a much larger potential code set size which can be tackled in
 a single run of mapping a particular template.

--

So Test #2 represents the best we could do with the 2 phase model ... so far
 at least.  FCDR w/ var ordering is  always nearly the best heuristic in 
 many many empirical evaluations of CSPs ... other more complicated ones
 can be better (and at IJCAI some resuls show always better) but for a 
 relatively simple heuristic combination it is consistently good.

Test #4 represents the best MAP-CSP did on its own.  4 is better than
 2 across the board.  At 500 noise, #2's 95% Conf Interval is between
 7174 and 44663, while #4's is betwween 1309 and  1997.  At 1000 noise,
 2 ranges between 50315 and 61947, while 4 ranges between only
 3808 and 5878.

Duplication of Search Effort:

I alluded to part of the explanation before I think ... the 2 phase approach
 essentially finds all N index matches ... and generates N secondary problems
 (I term these resolution problems) in which we hope that the non-solution
 bearing problems will yield this up right away.  To some extent this 
 happens, however, in the process (particular if N is large), it is quite
 possible that the beginning parts of the N resolution search spaces look
 quite similar (and certainly parts will be nearly identical).  In these
 similar spaces, a given constraint check between two candidate statements
 will be checked many times (up to N I suppose).  This redundancy is
 missed in the single-level problem solution.  So there is a tradeoff-
 the 2 phase splitting eliminates a large search portion and essentially
 focuses on N sub-parts of the space (while the whole problem cant do this), 
 but gives some savings back by duplicating parts of the exploration in
 constraint checks.  There are quite likely possibilities for 
 improving this performance with a specially modified search algorithm
 that factors out commonalities perhaps.  This would be a lot of work, but
 is something to keep in mind.  I suspect that a bit more looking into
 Freuder and Mackworth's work on this matter would yield some possibilities.
 I will save this for later on .... 


So we are left with : the 2 phase method works quite well, can be improved
 directly with FCDR w/ adv sort in place of a simple generic indexing strategy
 or non-generic application-specific strategy.   However, the FCDR w/ adv sort
 working on the entire problem at once still does better.  In effect it
 performs some kind of indexing which it determines dynamically based on 
 the problem instance, and then doesn't duplicate any search space as
 is the case with the 2 phase method.  I challenge anyone to show this
 result theoretically rather than empirically :-).   At least I don't know
 of anyone ... Perhaps Peter van Beek would have a comment about this ... also
 a good point for later.




